The paper discusses the use of revealed preference techniques in mechanism design for combinatorial auctions, which falls under the category of game theory (cs.GT). The paper also discusses the use of algorithms and computational methods to implement these mechanisms, which falls under the categories of artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and data structures and algorithms (cs.DS). The paper also discusses the use of virtual valuation functions to quantify the welfare guarantees of these mechanisms, which falls under the category of computational economics (cs.EC). Finally, the paper discusses the use of relaxed revealed preference constraints, which falls under the category of machine learning (cs.LG).
